3.We just pulled a new image. What is the tag on the newly pulled NGINX image?
Run the docker images / docker image ls command and look for the TAG column.

4.We just downloaded the code of an application. What is the base image used in the Dockerfile?
Inspect the Dockerfile in the webapp-color directory.
You can either open the file using vi /root/webapp-color/Dockerfile or using commands such as cat/more/less/vim e.t.c.
Then, look for the FROM instruction or search for it directly using:
grep -i FROM /root/webapp-color/Dockerfile
root@docker-host ~ ➜  vi /root/webapp-color/Dockerfile

root@docker-host ~ ➜  grep -i FROM /root/webapp-color/Dockerfile
FROM python:3.14

5.Based on the given Dockerfile, which instruction defines the command that starts the application when a container is started?
Inspect the Dockerfile in the webapp-color directory.

The following line in the Dockerfile shows the command that starts the application:
ENTRYPOINT ["python", "app.py"]

6.What port is the web application run within the container?
Inspect the Dockerfile in the webapp-color directory.

The following line in the Dockerfile shows the exposed port in the application:
EXPOSE 8080
7.Build a docker image using the Dockerfile and name it webapp-color. Do not specify a tag.

First, move to the directory by using the cd command, then verify the working directory path using the pwd command:
root@docker-host ~ ➜ cd /root/webapp-color/
root@docker-host ~ ➜ pwd
/root/webapp-color
Now, run the docker build command within that directory:
root@docker-host ~ ➜ docker build -t webapp-color . 
OR
root@docker-host ~ ➜ docker buildx build -t webapp-color . 
This uses the default docker BuildKit builder.
At the end of the command, the "." (dot) symbol refers to the current directory, so you need to run this command from within the directory that contains the Dockerfile.

root@docker-host ~ ➜  cd /root/webapp-color/

